===Etymology===
From {{term|abandon|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|abandonne|abandonné|immoral|lang=fr}} past participle of {{term|abandonner|lang=fr}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# [[self|Self]]-abandoned, or given up to vice; [[immoral]]; [[extremely]] wicked, or [[sinning]] without restraint; [[irreclaimably]] wicked; as, an ''abandoned'' [[villain]]. {{defdate|First attested from 1350 to 1470}}<ref name =SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref>
# No longer maintained by its former owners, residents{{,}} or caretakers; [[forsaken]], [[deserted]]. {{defdate|Late 15th century}}<ref name =SOED/>
#* {{rfdate}}, [[Thomson]]:
#*: {{...}} your '''abandoned''' streams {{...}}
# Free from constraint; [[uninhibited]]. {{defdate|Late 17th century}}<ref name =SOED/>
#* '''1919''', [[w:William Somerset Maugham|W. Somerset Maugham]], ''[[w:The Moon and Sixpence|The Moon and Sixpence]]'', [[s:The Moon and Sixpence/Chapter XI|chapter 11]]:
#*: Everything was dirty and [[shabby]]. There was no sign of the '''abandoned''' luxury that Colonel MacAndrew had so confidently described. 
# {{context|geology|lang=en}} No longer being acted upon by the geologic forces that formed it.

